items.title: Corunastylis ciliata
items.content_text: Flowering time Feb - Jun.  Dorsal sepal and petals usually bright green, labellum purplish with sparse hairs.  Plant usually difficult to see in habitat due to small size.

items.title: Corunastylis archeri
items.content_text: Flowering time Nov - March.  Grows in many habitats.  Flower dorsal sepal and petals lack hairs, labellum is fringed with medium to longish hairs.

items.title: Caladenia transitoria
items.content_text: Flowering period Oct - Nov.  Plant usually about 100mm tall and difficult to see in habitat.  Labellum has dark purple calli and petals usually yellowish-green.

items.title: Caladenia cucullata
items.content_text: Flowers are white, labellum has red to purple calli.  Common in inland areas.

items.title: Grevillea micrantha
items.content_text: The Brisbane Ranges form has leaves with granules confined to the veins on upper surface and broader grooves on undersurface.  Found mainly in western and central Victoria.  The climate is hot dry summers, cold wet winters, rainfall around 500mm annually.

items.title: Grevillea micrantha
items.content_text: Commonly known as Small-leaf Grevillea.  The flowers are white to pale pink and often hidden in the dull green foliage.

items.title: Thelymitra spp.
items.content_text: This is a natural hybrid between Thelymitra holmesii and Thelymitra ixioides.  It was photographed at the edge of a swamp area.

items.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
items.content_text: This moth was making use of the nectar provided by the wildflower.

items.title: Leporella fimbriata
items.content_text:
Flowers in Autumn (Apr - Jun), favours heathland and woodland with heath under-story usually in sandy soil.
This species often grows in large colonies and flowers prolifically only after fire.
This form is very unusual.

items.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
items.content_text: This grevillea is a low spreading shrub with shiny, lightly toothed, holly-like leaves and bright red toothbrush flowers.  It is found in Victoria, mostly confined to the Brisbane Ranges between Geelong & Bacchus marsh.  Grows in dry, open eucalypt forest

items.title: Thelymitra matthewsii
items.content_text:
Flowers in Spring (Sep), favours poor gravelly soil, mainly coastal, often in areas that have been disturbed.
The flower is temperamental and reluctant to open unless circumstances are exactly right.

items.title: Pterostylis smaragdyna
items.content_text:
Flowers in Winter (Jun - Aug), favours low flats, well drained - loamy soil in open forest.
Labellum contains small bristles and retracts when disturbed.  Lateral sepals touching at base of flower.

items.title: Caladenia clavescens
items.content_text:
Flowers in Spring (Sep - Oct) - Heavy soils, often rocky, on ridges or slopes in woodland and box-ironbark forest.
